{"type":"message","id":"8f02eb37","parentId":"8be7d14d","timestamp":"2026-03-21T17:37:49.215Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Bobby wants a reminder later about cleaning his X account. Since I'm not using cron jobs anymore, I just need to remember to text him later. But since I'm not always running, I should set a reminder for myself somehow. \n\nThe problem is - I can't use cron jobs (they send those system confirmations). But I can set a cron job for a specific time and just... not have it send a system message? No, that's not how it works.\n\nActually, wait - the issue is that OpenClaw sends those system confirmations after cron jobs. What if I just... note the time Bobby wants to be reminded, and then send it myself? I can't rely on a cron job to remind me, because I'd need to be paying attention.\n \nThe simplest solution is to just tell Bobby I'll reach out around that time - 9:30 PM seems to be his usual reminder window - without setting up an automated cron job that triggers system messages. I could set a one-shot cron that fires at a specific time and just hope I'm active to send the message myself when it triggers. I'm realizing the core issue: I need to actually be present in a session when that 9:30 PM reminder fires, otherwise I'll miss it entirely. I can't rely on being awake or available at that exact moment without some kind of passive notification system keeping me informed about what I need to do. I'll just set a simple reminder for 9:30 PM and send it to him directly when that time comes. If I'm not in an active session, the cron job will trigger anyway, so he should get the message either way. I'm going in circles here—the real issue is that I can't actually guarantee being available at 9:30 PM to send the reminder myself. The honest move is to just tell Bobby I'll do my best to remember and send it then, without pretending I have a system that works reliably.","thinkingSignature":"83898cb4d3a8168660b0a00b